content.description: Start on the inside corner.  At the ledge at mid-height, head up through the slight overhang into the crack on the left.  Continue to the top.
content.protection: Lots of opportunities for gear on this one.  Take one large hand - or fist-sized piece for just above the little overhang.
content.location: On the first buttress south of Dead Tree Wall, and south of the the Dead Tree Wall access route.  In a mini-amphitheater.  A small thumb of rock at the top makes for an easy top-anchor.

content.description: Not to be missed!  10 Ft. right of Dead Tree Route.  Crux is the first 15 feet- a thin tips crack with tricky smears for the feet on left and toe scum in crack opening on the right.  Stab for jug above.  Excellent pro abounds. Then follow very interesting crack and edges line to top.  There is a second and mid way crux when making move from large flake on left up to cool mantle ledge.  Upper moves are stellar as well and the whole thing is OK protected... there are a few spots one has to go a body length without protection.
content.protection: One fixed pin towards top of the route.  Small to medium wires, small three cams, Ball nuts.
content.location: Right side of Dead Tree Wall.

content.description: Begin on the outer corner that marks the left edge of the ampitheater.  Climb up beside flakes on the left, to the top.
content.protection: Not much until you are past the crux.
content.location: On the first buttress south of Dead Tree Wall, in a mini amphitheater.  A thumb of rock at the top makes for an easy TR setup.  Swartling & Mayer 282:14.

content.description: Climb Amazing Grace to upper overhang pull it directly and a few hard cranks and you are over.
content.protection: Rich Bechler, lead it, Trad, TR

content.description: Distinct from and separate route just right of Tardis.   Climb broken rock and cracks just right of Tardis finger crack start up to horizontal.  Climb face right of the middle crack section of Tardis trending rightwards to hanging crack with very sharp finger lock (you will know when you get it).  Exit onto slabs above and climb the final upper moves of Tardis utilizing the fixed pin for pro.
content.protection: Excellent.  Stoppers small to mid sized, small cams.
content.location: Dead Tree Wall.... just right of the route Tardis.  Shares the same finish as Tardis.

content.protection: TR, might make a good headpoint.
content.location: Climb a shallow dihedral and tight seam 5 ft left of Dead Tree climb. Angle left towards right side of large overhang past a small shrub on the wall.

content.description: Two cruxes....  One low getting through the initial steep crack section to reach ledges and holds under the second harder crux which pulls the devious moderate overhang past the "Dead Tree", now actually a rotted stump.  Very exiting and no give away for the grade.
content.protection: Excellent all the way.  Typical DL  rack with assorted sizes and types of pro.
content.location: Prominent central crack line of Dead Tree Wall.

content.description: Start at the end of the corner and climb up to the stump. Follow the corner to the top.
content.protection: Good anchors at the top, good pro.
content.location: To the far right of Dr. Who

content.description: Climbs narrow face, between Dead Tree climb and Tardis, tricky face climbing leads to a hard crank over a roof to face staying left of Tardis,

Climb the inside corner until it ends about half way up. Then it's easy climbing until you get to the finishing moves at the prow on top.

 It's an interesting route, just not an amazing one like its neighbor to the right. The route is unnamed in the guide books - S/M #17, Knower #5.
content.location: On the left side of Dead Tree Wall proper, and left of Amazing Grace.

content.description: Climb onto the detached block below 1st overhang, pass the overhang on the right, pass upper overhang on the left.  There is a variation that traverses right at the top.
content.protection: TR, or run it way out.

content.description: Nice Steep 50 to 60 Ft. wall with good routes to be found just to the north of Reclining Tower area as one walks north along the West Bluff Trail.  The top of Dead Tree Wall is very close to to the trail.  Wall doesn't really see any more or less shade or sunshine then most other West Bluff Crags. There is a prominent central crack line called....you guessed it... "Dead Tree Crack".
